**Update: This answer was posted before the main question had been answered. I am leaving the answer in place as a reference, but I am leaving a comment that it is about to be updated.**
The answer is that you've found the limit of the code that you're using.
When you use loops, the number of times the loop runs is limited by the first variable you assign to it.
In your code, you're assigning the variable dt to the first value of dt, which is 0.
The second time through the loop you're assigning it to the first value of dt, which is 1.
This is because of the way C (or C++) variables work. Consider this pseudo-code:
int i = 1;
for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    i++;
}

In a situation like this, the value of i will be 3.
In order to fix your code, you can use a loop counter outside of the loop, like so:
for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
    a[i] = i;
}

That way, the value of i will always be 0, 1, and 2, even when the loop has finished running.

A:

You have to remember that the size of an array is determined by the highest index you access.
So if you have:
int a[3];

Then you can access the 5th element with:
a[4] = 6;

But you can't do:
a[5] = 7;

because it's out of bounds.
If you want to do:
a[4] = 7;

Then you have to know the size of the array before hand.
The solution to your problem is to keep track of the size of your array with a separate variable, and use that variable when you enter the loop.
int size = 3;

for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) {
  a[i] = i;
}

