Q:

C++ ifstream file not found

I am new to C++ and have been working on a program but I am stuck at the ifstream line. I am getting the error "ifstream file not found" in the ifstream is. How can I fix this?
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
    ifstream file;
    string input;
    cout << "Enter your string: " << endl;
    getline(cin, input);

    file.open("test.txt");
    if (file.is_open())
    {
        file >> input;
    }
    else
    {
        cout << "invalid file name" << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

A:

You need to open the file test.txt as follows:
file.open("test.txt", ios::in);

You need to use the flag ios::in to open the file.

A:

The ifstream constructor requires:
ifstream(const char*)

However, your code passes in test.txt for the file name. You can fix this by using:
file.open("test.txt", ios::in | ios::out);

The ios::in flag tells open() that the file is to be opened for reading. The ios::out flag tells open() that the file is to be opened for writing.

