The subject matter disclosed herein generally relates to a method for forming an interconnect material, and more particularly to a method for forming an interconnect structure for a semiconductor device.
In semiconductor fabrication, metal interconnects may be used to interconnect various components. Metal interconnects may be formed by depositing a dielectric material such as silicon dioxide. A conductive material such as copper, copper alloy, aluminum, aluminum alloy, or tungsten may be deposited over the dielectric material to fill the spaces and provide the interconnects. The conductive material may then be polished to remove an excess amount of the conductive material. The excess amount of the conductive material may form a thin layer of conductive material at the surface of the interconnect structure. The thin layer of conductive material may be referred to as a “spike”. The removal of the excess amount of the conductive material may be performed using a CMP process.
It may be desirable to reduce the size of semiconductor devices. As the size of semiconductor devices is reduced, the distance between the conductive material within the interconnect structure may be reduced. The removal of the excess amount of the conductive material may be difficult, and may lead to the formation of the spikes at the surface of the interconnect structure. The spikes may cause reliability issues and may lead to an increase in contact resistance and contact electromigration.
Accordingly, it is desirable to provide improved methods for forming an interconnect structure for a semiconductor device.Q:

